{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b3e2624da6c3fb52", "type": "tool_result", "content": "100\tspeakers, where both the utterances and speakers are entirely\n101\tnew to the model. The SpireEMA dataset is open-source and\n102\tpublicly available on Hugging Face 1\n103\tFor pretraining, we use the LibriSpeech ASR dataset [29],\n104\tspecifically the train-100 subset, which contains 100 hours of\n105\tspeech data. To obtain frame-level phoneme alignments, we\n106\tprocess the data using the Kaldi toolkit [30].\n107\t\n108\t3. Methodology\n109\tIn this work, we investigate different pretraining targets for AAI\n110\tand subsequently fine-tune the model using varying amounts of\n111\tEMA data. The trained models are then evaluated on the test set\n112\tto assess their effectiveness. For pretraining, we explore three\n113\tdistinct target representations:\n114\t• Phoneme Labels: We use frame-aligned phoneme labels as\n115\tground truth for classification. The model is trained using\n116\tCross-Entropy loss to predict the phoneme label corresponding to each frame.\n117\t• Articulatory Feature Labels: Inspired by [31], we use articulatory feature classes as ground truth labels. Specifically, we\n118\tpredict four articulatory attributes—place, manner, height,\n119\tand backness—by employing four separate linear layers at\n120\tthe model’s output. The ground truth labels for each phoneme\n121\t1 https://huggingface.co/datasets/SpireLab/\n122\tSPIRE_EMA_CORPUS\n123\t\n124\tTable 1: Articulatory feature labels for pretraining\n125\t\n126\tFeature\n127\tPlace\n128\tManner\n129\tHeight\n130\tBackness\n131\t\n132\tPossible Values\n133\tbilabial, labiodental, dental, alveolar,\n134\tpostalveolar, palatal, velar, glottal, vowel, silence\n135\tstop, affricate, fricative, nasal,\n136\tapproximant, lateral, vowel, silence\n137\tclose, nearclose, closemid, mid,\n138\topenmid, nearopen, open, consonant, silence\n139\tfront, central, back, consonant, silence\n140\t\n141\tare derived from the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\n142\tchart2 , with details provided in Table 1. As this is a classification task, we use Cross-Entropy loss for optimization.\n143\t• Critical-articulator Labels: Following [32], we identify\n144\tcritical articulators for 13 specific phonemes. Using this\n145\tinformation, we construct a 12-dimensional binary vector,\n146\ttermed the critical-articulator label, for each input frame.\n147\tEach element in this vector is set to 1 for articulators that\n148\tare critical for the given phoneme and 0 otherwise. For\n149\tphonemes outside the set of 13, all values in the vector are\n150\tset to 0. The model is trained to predict this 12-dimensional\n151\tvector using a sigmoid activation function, and we optimize\n152\tthe predictions using Binary Cross-Entropy loss. Additionally, for frames corresponding to phonemes outside the predefined set, we mask the loss to avoid penalising the model\n153\tfor missing articulatory information.\n154\tAfter pretraining, we removed the final output layer of the\n155\tmodel, which was used to predict the pretraining targets, and replaced it with a 12-dimensional linear layer for predicting EMA\n156\ttrajectories in the AAI task. We adopt a non-autoregressive\n157\ttransformer-based neural network architecture [33], similar to\n158\tthe model used in [14].\n159\t\n160\t4. Experimental Setup\n161\t4.0.1. Pretraining Configurations\n162\tWe explore different pretraining configurations by combining\n163\tvarious target representations. The configurations are as follows:\n164\t• ACP-T: Pretraining is conducted using all three target\n165\ttypes—Articulatory Feature Labels, Critical-articulator Labels, and Phoneme Labels.\n166\t• AC-T: This configuration utilizes Articulatory Feature Labels and Critical-articulator Labels for pretraining.\n167\t• AP-T: Pretraining is performed with Articulatory Feature\n168\tLabels and Phoneme Labels.\n169\t• CP-T: This setup employs Critical-articulator Labels and\n170\tPhoneme Labels as pretraining targets.\n171\t• P-T: Only Phoneme Labels are used for pretraining.\n172\t• C-T: Pretraining is conducted exclusively with Criticalarticulator Labels.\n173\t• A-T: Only Articulatory Feature Labels are utilized for pretraining.\n174\t4.0.2. Input Configurations\n175\tWe experiment with two different input feature types:\n176\t• MFCC: We use 13-dimensional MFCC as input to the model.\n177\t• TERA: We use 768-dimensional features extracted from the\n178\t2 https://www.internationalphoneticassociation.\n179\torg/content/full-ipa-chart\n180\t\n181\t\fTable 2: CC and RMSE for different configurations with MFCC inputs for seen speakers test set\n182\tEMA data used for training (%)\n183\tCC (Std)\n184\tBaseline\n185\tRMSE (Std)\n186\tCC (Std)\n187\tACP-T\n188\tRMSE (Std)\n189\tCC (Std)\n190\tAC-T\n191\tRMSE (Std)\n192\tCC (Std)\n193\tAP-T\n194\tRMSE (Std)\n195\tCC (Std)\n196\tCP-T\n197\tRMSE (Std)\n198\tCC (Std)\n199\tP-T\n200\tRMSE (Std)\n201\tCC (Std)\n202\tC-T\n203\tRMSE (Std)\n204\tCC (Std)\n205\tA-T\n206\tRMSE (Std)\n207\t\n208\t6.25\n209\t0.7348 (0.1652)\n210\t1.4394 (0.3695)\n211\t0.7811 (0.1518)\n212\t1.3535 (0.3580)\n213\t0.7779 (0.1552)\n214\t1.3538 (0.3585)\n215\t0.7782 (0.1522)\n216\t1.3550 (0.3529)\n217\t0.7774 (0.1548)\n218\t1.3619 (0.3490)\n219\t0.7806 (0.152)\n220\t1.3539 (0.3580)\n221\t0.7718 (0.1525)\n222\t1.3639 (0.3600)\n223\t0.7773 (0.1547)\n224\t1.355 (0.3560)\n225\t\n226\t12.5\n227\t0.7857 (0.1453)\n228\t1.3180 (0.3535)\n229\t0.8112 (0.1370)\n230\t1.2620 (0.3515)\n231\t0.8121(0.1358)\n232\t1.2602 (0.3468)\n233\t0.8095 (0.1403)\n234\t1.2749 (0.3529)\n235\t0.8101 (0.1384)\n236\t1.2530 (0.3449)\n237\t0.8097 (0.1361)\n238\t1.2602 (0.3472)\n239\t0.8027 (0.1403)\n240\t1.2810 (0.3470)\n241\t0.8101 (0.1377)\n242\t1.2699 (0.3479)\n243\t\n244\t25\n245\t0.8254 (0.1253)\n246\t1.1964 (0.3407)\n247\t0.8379 (0.1251)\n248\t1.1694 (0.3371)\n249\t0.8380 (0.1231)\n250\t1.1719 (0.3