ns with MFCC and TERA inputs for unseen speakers test set\n579\tEMA data used for training (%)\n580\tInputs\n581\tModels\n582\tCC (Std)\n583\tBaseline\n584\tRMSE (Std)\n585\tMFCC\n586\tCC (Std)\n587\tACP-T\n588\tRMSE (Std)\n589\tCC (Std)\n590\tBaseline\n591\tRMSE (Std)\n592\tTERA\n593\tCC (Std)\n594\tACP-T\n595\tRMSE (Std)\n596\t\n597\t6.25\n598\t\n599\t12.5\n600\t\n601\t25\n602\t\n603\t50\n604\t\n605\t75\n606\t\n607\t100\n608\t\n609\t0.6687 (0.2020)\n610\t1.5992 (0.3842)\n611\t0.7259 (0.1872)\n612\t1.5241 (0.4001)\n613\t0.7325 (0.1834)\n614\t1.4788 (0.4027)\n615\t0.7561 (0.1697)\n616\t1.3999 (0.3770)\n617\t\n618\t0.6991 (0.1996)\n619\t1.5540 (0.4050)\n620\t0.7399 (0.1814)\n621\t1.4779 (0.4041)\n622\t0.7396 (0.1890)\n623\t1.4515 (0.4113)\n624\t0.7562 (0.1782)\n625\t1.4110 (0.3889)\n626\t\n627\t0.7265 (0.1876)\n628\t1.4854 (0.3980)\n629\t0.7469 (0.1875)\n630\t1.4514 (0.4043)\n631\t0.7540 (0.1731)\n632\t1.4160 (0.4040)\n633\t0.7621 (0.1768)\n634\t1.4110 (0.3970)\n635\t\n636\t0.7488 (0.1783)\n637\t1.4357 (0.3962)\n638\t0.7616 (0.1796)\n639\t1.4160 (0.4060)\n640\t0.7664 (0.1782)\n641\t1.3860 (0.4070)\n642\t0.7755 (0.1718)\n643\t1.3849 (0.4070)\n644\t\n645\t0.7488 (0.1783)\n646\t1.4357 (0.3962)\n647\t0.7653 (0.1803)\n648\t1.4160 (0.4059)\n649\t0.7777 (0.1725)\n650\t1.3774 (0.4120)\n651\t0.7818 (0.1719)\n652\t1.3600 (0.4140)\n653\t\n654\t0.7563 (0.1822)\n655\t1.4143 (0.4040)\n656\t0.7689 (0.1823)\n657\t1.3848 (0.4154)\n658\t0.7717 (0.1769)\n659\t1.3878 (0.4154)\n660\t0.7810 (0.1758)\n661\t1.3619 (0.4210)\n662\t\n663\tperformance for low-resource conditions (6.25% to 25%). This\n664\tsuggests that pretraining enhances the generalization ability of\n665\tAAI models.\n666\t1. 100% training data: The ACP-T configuration achieves the\n667\thighest performance (CC: 0.8612, RMSE: 1.1023), indicating that incorporating all three auxiliary targets provides the\n668\tbest generalization.\n669\t2. 6.25% training data: The A-T configuration performs best\n670\t(CC: 0.7324, RMSE: 1.4900), suggesting that when extremely limited data is available, using only articulatory labels during pretraining still provides a strong foundation.\n671\t3. Interestingly, many pretraining configurations fine-tuned on\n672\tjust 50% of the training data outperforms the baseline\n673\tmodel trained on the full dataset, reinforcing the efficiency of pretraining in reducing the reliance on large labelled datasets.\n674\t4.1.3. Comparing MFCC and TERA Inputs\n675\tTables 4 and 5 compare the impact of input types—MFCC vs.\n676\tTERA—under the ACP-T pretraining configuration.\n677\t1. TERA consistently outperforms MFCC, confirming that\n678\tSSL features provide richer speech representations, leading\n679\tto better articulatory inversion performance.\n680\t2. However, MFCC with pretraining achieves performance\n681\tclose to or better than the baseline TERA model, especially in low-resource scenarios (6.25%–25%).\n682\t3. In Table 4 (seen speakers test set), for 6.25% to 25% of the\n683\ttraining data, ACP-T with MFCC input outperforms the\n684\tbaseline model with TERA input, further reinforcing the\n685\teffectiveness of pretraining in enhancing model performance\n686\teven with simpler input representations.\n687\tOverall, these results highlight the significant benefits of\n688\tpretraining for AAI, particularly in low-resource conditions,\n689\twhere it improves both seen and unseen speaker performance\n690\twhile enabling more efficient data utilization.\n691\t\n692\tdifferent pretraining targets and input types. Our experiments\n693\tdemonstrated that pretraining significantly improves model performance, particularly in low-resource settings.\n694\tOur key findings are as follows:\n695\t1. Pretraining consistently enhances AAI performance, particularly in low-resource conditions, where it significantly\n696\tboosts CC and reduces RMSE.\n697\t2. Pretraining improves generalization to unseen speakers,\n698\twith larger performance gains observed in this scenario compared to seen speakers.\n699\t3. Pretraining with MFCC input achieves performance\n700\tcomparable to or better than SSL-based models in certain\n701\tcases, reinforcing the value of our approach. This suggests\n702\tthat pretraining allows models to learn meaningful articulatory representations without requiring computationally expensive self-supervised feature extractors at inference time.\n703\t4. Models trained with TERA input still outperform those\n704\ttrained with MFCC input in most cases, confirming the advantages of SSL-based features for AAI. However, the ability\n705\tof pretraining to bridge this performance gap highlights its\n706\teffectiveness in reducing reliance on complex feature extractors.\n707\t5. By reducing computational overhead without sacrificing\n708\taccuracy, our method presents a more efficient alternative\n709\tfor AAI, making it particularly suitable for deployment in\n710\treal-time and resource-constrained environments.\n711\tThese results emphasize the importance of pretraining in\n712\tAAI models, particularly for low-resource settings and robust\n713\tgeneralization across speakers. In future work, we plan to explore additional pretraining strategies and target representations\n714\tto further enhance AAI performance. Investigating diverse pretraining objectives could improve generalization across speakers and data conditions, making AAI systems more adaptable\n715\tand effective.\n716\t\n717\t5. Conclusions\n718\t\n719\t6. Acknowledgement\n720\t\n721\tIn this work, we explored the impact of pretraining on the\n722\tArticulatory-to-Acoustic Inversion (AAI) task, investigating\n723\t\n724\tWe thank the Department of Science and Technology (DST),\n725\tGovernment of India, for supporting this work.\n726\t\n727\t\f7. References\n728\t[1] P. K. Ghosh and S. S. Narayanan, “A subject-independent\n729\tacoustic-to-articulatory inversion,” in 2011 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n730\t(ICASSP), 